(v. 78.) Α good story was that he told us when one commended the wealth of the miser Arellius, little knowing the anxiety it cost him.

“ Once upon a time,’' said he, ‘¹ a country mouse entertained a city friend in his hole: a shrewd thrifty meuse, but hospitable neverthelaes. Well, he put before him the best he had,—pulse and oats, and dry grape stones, and nibbled bits of lard,—to tempt his dainty palate, while he himself ate nought but coarser grains. Then at length says the gentleman from the town, ‘ How canst thou endure, my friend, to live in these wilds Ξ Wouldst thou not prefer the haunts of man to these rough woods? Then haste, come back with me; life is short3 we all must die; live cheerfully while thou mayst! So the clown jumps up, and off they set for the city. The night was at its noon when they entered the rich man’s house, where the bright coverlid clothed the ivery couch, and plenteous were the remains of the evening’s repast. Then the host sets his rustic friend on the fine couch, and girds himself up to attend him, changes the dishes, and tastes before he serves them. While the other is making men-y over his altered con- dition, lo! the doors creak upon their hinges, the watch-dogs bark, and the trembling friends rush hither and thither, till safe at last, says the countryman, ⁴ Ι like not this life of thine: farewell. In my hole in the woods Ι sear no surprises, and 1’11 make myself happy with my humble fare.' ''
